gut, ovary, or kidney).88 15% present with sudden

paraplegia and incontinence. Inﬁltration of bone

marrow is rare. Jaw involvement is common in young

children (peak ages of incidence 3–7 years).89 In low-

income countries, such as in sub-Saharan Africa, many

children present with advanced disease. In a study of

84 Malawian children with Burkitt’s lymphoma,

26 (31%) presented with facial disease only and 52 (62%)

with abdominal disease; 58 (69%) had St Jude stage III

or IV disease.88 Patients are commonly malnourished

at diagnosis.90

